{"title_page": "Quattro pezzi sacri", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Quattro pezzi sacri''\n| composer            = [[Giuseppe Verdi]]\n| genre               = [[Sacred music|Sacred vocal music]]\n| image               = File:Verdi-1899.jpg\n| alt                 = The composer in 1899\n| caption             = \n| translation         = ''Four Sacred Pieces''\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = it\n| text                = {{plainlist|\n* '''Ave Maria''' \u2013 [[Ave Maria]]\n* {{nowrap|'''Stabat Mater''' \u2013 [[Stabat Mater]]}}\n* '''Laudi alla Vergine Maria''' \u2013 Canto XXXIII from {{nowrap|Dante's ''[[Paradiso (Dante)|Paradiso]]''}}  \n* '''Te Deum''' \u2013 [[Te Deum]]\n}}\n| language            = {{flatlist|\n* Latin\n* Italian\n}}\n| composed            = {{Start date|1886}} \u2013 {{End date|1897}}\n| performed           = {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1898|04|07|df=y}}|location=[[Paris Opera]]}} (without ''Ave Maria'')\n| published           = {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1898}}|location=[[Milan]]}}\n| scoring             = \n| misc                = \n}}\n\nThe '''''Quattro pezzi sacri''''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8kwattro \u02c8p\u025bttsi \u02c8sa\u02d0kri}}, ''Four Sacred Pieces'') are choral works by [[Giuseppe Verdi]]. Written separately during the last decades of the composer's life and with different origins and purposes, they were nevertheless published together in 1898 by [[Casa Ricordi]]. They are often performed as a cycle, not in chronological sequence of their composition, but in the sequence used in the Ricordi publication:\n* '''Ave Maria''', a setting of the [[Latin]] [[Ave Maria]] for four solo voices [[a cappella]] composed in 1889  \n* '''Stabat Mater''', a setting of the Latin [[Stabat Mater]] for chorus and orchestra composed in 1896 and 1897 \n* '''Laudi alla Vergine Maria''', a setting of a prayer in Canto XXXIII of [[Dante]]'s ''[[Paradiso (Dante)|Paradiso]]'' for four female voices a cappella composed between 1886 and 1888 \n* '''Te Deum''', a setting of the Latin [[Te Deum]] for double chorus and orchestra composed in 1895 and 1896.\n\nThey were first performed together (without the Ave Maria) in a concert by the [[Paris Opera]] on April 7, 1898.\n\n== History ==\n\nAfter Verdi finished his opera ''[[Aida]]'' and in 1874 the [[Requiem (Verdi)|Messa da Requiem]], he retired from composing for years, writing only minor sacred compositions such as a Pater Noster and an Ave Maria in 1880.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=351}} The earliest of the ''Quattro pezzi sacri'' in terms of its composition date is what came to be known as Laudi alla Vergine Maria (although Verdi himself did not give it that title).{{sfn|Izzo|2013|p= 318}} It was composed between 1886 and 1888, during which time he was also working on his penultimate opera, ''[[Otello]]'', which premiered in 1887. The second of the ''Pezzi'' to be composed was the Ave Maria, whose setting is built on an [[enigmatic scale]]. He originally composed it in 1889 and revised it for publication in 1897. The Te Deum was begun in 1895 two years after the premiere of his last opera, ''[[Falstaff (opera)|Falstaff]]''. It was finished in the summer of 1896. The Stabat Mater followed, and all four pieces were sent to Verdi's publisher, [[Casa Ricordi]], in June 1897.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=145}}\n\n== Music ==\nAt the end of his life Verdi returned to his beginnings as a church musician.{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}}  He studied [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]'s [[Mass in B minor structure|Mass in B minor]] and compositions by [[Giovanni Pierluigi da Palestrina|Palestrina]],{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} whose influence is apparent in the Laudi alla Vergine Maria.\n\nThe publisher [[Schott Music|Schott]] gives the total performance time as 37 minutes.<ref name=\"Schott\">''[https://archive.is/20131009105052/http://www.schott-music.com/shop/noten/eulenburg_studien-partituren/1660493/1261864/show,47227.html Four Sacred Pieces]'' [[Schott Music|Schott]]. Retrieved 9 October 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Ave Maria ===\n[[File:Scala enigmatica.svg|Enigmatic scale on C, base for Verdi's Ave Maria]]\n\nVerdi was inspired in 1889 to compose Ave Maria by the [[enigmatic scale]] C \u2013 D-flat \u2013 E \u2013 F-sharp \u2013 G-sharp \u2013 A-sharp \u2013 B \u2013 C which [[Adolfo Crescentini]] (1854\u20131921) had published in Ricordi's magazine ''Gazetta musicale di Milano'', inviting composers to harmonise it.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=135}} Verdi composed a setting for four unaccompanied voices, with the [[Bass (voice type)|bass]] singing the scale first, followed by [[alto]], [[tenor]] and [[soprano]], whereas the three remaining voices supply harmonic texture.{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} He commented: \"An Ave Maria. It will be my fourth! Perhaps I shall be beatified by the Holy Father.\"{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=135}} Verdi revised the work in June 1897 for the publication.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=145}} The music publisher [[Schott Music|Schott]] renders the subtitle as \"Scala enigmatica armonizzata a 4 voci miste\" (Enigmatic scale harmonised for four mixed voices).<ref name=\"Schott\" /> It takes about six minutes to perform.\n\n=== Stabat Mater ===\nWhile Ave Maria is set for soloists, Verdi scored the Stabat Mater for a four-part mixed chorus ([[SATB]]) and a large orchestra of three [[flute]]s, two [[oboe]]s, two [[clarinet]]s. four [[bassoon]]s, four [[French horn|horn]]s, three [[trumpet]]s, four [[trombone]]s, [[percussion]] ([[timpani]] and [[bass drum]]), [[harp]] and [[string instrument|string]]s.\n\nThe work is through-composed, without repetition of text. It is full of chromaticism. Melodic parts, similar to arias, contrast with [[a cappella]] passages and dramatic outbursts. The music reaches a climax on the text \"Paradisi gloria\" (glory of paradise), then dies down in the lowest registers of the strings.{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} A performance takes about 12 minutes.\n\n=== Laudi alla Vergine Maria ===\nLaudi alla Vergine Maria is another a cappella work, set for four solo female voices. It is based on a short prayer from in Canto XXXIII of Dantes's ''[[Paradiso (Dante)|Paradiso]]'', the third part of his ''[[Divina Commedia]]''. Verdi alludes on the counterpoint of [[Renaissance music]]. Each stanza is introduced by a new motif. Biographer Budden describes the piece as \"with the subtlest of harmonic and rhythmic inflexions, unashamedly modern in character\". The audience requested a repetition when it was first performed.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|pp=352\u2013353}}{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} Publisher Schott renders the subtitle as \"Tolte dall' ultimo canto del \"Paradiso\" di Dante per 4 voci feminili, sole\" (Taken from the ultimate song of \"Paradiso\" by Dante for 4 female voices, solo).<ref name=\"Schott\" /> It takes about six minutes to perform.\n\n=== Te Deum ===\nThe Ambrosian Hymn Te Deum is scored for two four-part choirs, a short soprano solo and large orchestra, adding [[cor anglais]] and [[bass clarinet]] to the orchestra of the ''Stabat Mater'', but without harp.{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} Verdi wrote to Giovanni Tebaldini, director of music in Padua: \"It is usually sung during grand, solemn and noisy ceremonies for a victory or a coronation etc. ... Humanity believes in the Judex Venturus, invokes Him in the Salvum fac and ends with a prayer, 'Dignare Domine die isto', which is moving, melancholy and sad even to the point of terror.\"{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=145}} The music begins with the [[Gregorian chant]] ''Te deum laudamus, te Dominum confitemur'', continued [[Responsory|responsorially]] by the whole male choir in [[unison]]. The full choir and orchestra enter in partly dramatic scenes, reminiscent of the Messa da Requiem,{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} interspersed by Gregorian chant. The final line ''in te speravi'' is first rendered by a single soprano voice from the choir, representing the \"[voice of] mankind\", as Verdi requested. The line is repeated by the choir, followed by a reticent postlude, similar to the conclusion of the [[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]].{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} A performance takes about 15 minutes. Verdi himself suggested 12 minutes.\n\n== Performances ==\nVerdi did not want the Ave Maria to be performed with the other pieces.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=353}} According to his wish, three pieces were first performed on 7 and 8 April 1898 at the [[Paris Opera]] as part of a concert series of the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Concerts du Conservatoire, conducted by [[Paul Taffanel]] (1844\u20131908). Verdi was not present, because he had suffered a mild stroke, but sent [[Arrigo Boito]] with several requests, partly in writing, for performance details. The first performance in Italy, again without the ''Ave Maria'', was conducted in [[Turin]] on 26 May 1898 by [[Arturo Toscanini]] who had talked to Verdi. The first performance in Austria on 13 November 1898 in Vienna was conducted by [[Richard von Perger]] and included the ''Ave Maria'',{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=353}} but the two a cappella works were performed by the choir, not by solo voices as Verdi had intended.{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}}\n\nVerdi liked the Te Deum best of the four works and reputedly wanted to be buried with the score.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=358}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv | last = Budden | first = Julian | url = https://books.google.com/?id=wKpapMfOp8kC&dq=Quattro+pezzi+sacri,+verdi | title = Verdi | year = 2008 | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | accessdate = 8 October 2013|isbn=9780198043485}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv |editor-first= Anselm |editor-last = Gerhard | editor-first2=Uwe | editor-last2=Schweikert |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=vXo3AQAAIAAJ|first=Uwe|last=Schweikert | chapter= Quattro pezzi sacri |title=Verdi Handbuch| year = 2001 | publisher = Metzler | location = Metzler Kassel, B\u00e4renreiter Stuttgart and Weimar |isbn=9783476017680|language=German }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv |last=Izzo|first= Francesco|editor-last=Di Grazia|editor-first=Donna M. |chapter=A Tale of Survival: Choral Music in Italy|title=Nineteenth-Century Choral Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AMog9DiN0jAC&pg=PA318|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415988520|page=318}}\n{{refend}}\n* Rizzo, Dino (2014). \"La Musica filosofica nei tre Pezzi sacri di Verdi\". In ''Atti del Convegno Verdi, la Musica e il Sacro, Roncole Verdi - Busseto, 27-29 settembre 2013'' a cura di Dino Rizzo, Fidenza, Mattioli 1885. {{ISBN|9788862614382}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMSLP|work=4 Pezzi sacri (Verdi, Giuseppe)|cname=Quattro pezzi sacri}}\n* {{ChoralWiki|Ave_Maria_(Giuseppe_Verdi)|Giuseppe Verdi: Ave Maria}}\n* {{ChoralWiki|Laudi_alla_Vergine_Maria_(Giuseppe_Verdi)|Giuseppe Verdi: Laudi alla Vergine Maria}}\n* {{DNB portal|30016615X}}\n* [http://www.allmusic.com/composition/sacred-pieces-4-for-chorus-orchestra-quattro-pezzi-sacri-mc0002363490 Giuseppe Verdi / Sacred Pieces (4), for chorus & orchestra (Quattro pezzi sacri)] [[Allmusic]]\n* Irina Georgieva: [https://urresearch.rochester.edu/fileDownloadForInstitutionalItem.action?itemId=26100&itemFileId=86306 Giuseppe Verdi's Quattro Pezzi Sacri: Early History and Programming Considerations, Analysis, and Interpretation] [[Eastman School of Music]], Rochester, New York\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150610202753/http://www.carus-verlag.com/index.php3?selSprache=1&BLink=KKArtikel&ArtNummer=2750000 Verdi\u2019s Quattro Pezzi Sacri] [[Carus-Verlag]]\n\n{{Giuseppe Verdi|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Giuseppe Verdi]]\n[[Category:Choral compositions]]\n[[Category:Stabat Mater settings|Verdi]]\n[[Category:Te Deums|Verdi]]\n[[Category:1898 compositions]]\n[[Category:Musical settings of poems by Dante Alighieri]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Quattro pezzi sacri''\n| composer            = [[Giuseppe Verdi]]\n| genre               = [[Sacred music|Sacred vocal music]]\n| image               = File:Verdi-1899.jpg\n| alt                 = The composer in 1899\n| caption             = \n| translation         = ''Four Sacred Pieces''\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = it\n| text                = {{plainlist|\n* '''Ave Maria''' \u2013 [[Ave Maria]]\n* {{nowrap|'''Stabat Mater''' \u2013 [[Stabat Mater]]}}\n* '''Laudi alla Vergine Maria''' \u2013 Canto XXXIII from {{nowrap|Dante's ''[[Paradiso (Dante)|Paradiso]]''}}  \n* '''Te Deum''' \u2013 [[Te Deum]]\n}}\n| language            = {{flatlist|\n* Latin\n* Italian\n}}\n| composed            = {{Start date|1886}} \u2013 {{End date|1897}}\n| performed           = {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1898|04|07|df=y}}|location=[[Paris Opera]]}} (without ''Ave Maria'')\n| published           = {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1898}}|location=[[Milan]]}}\n| scoring             = \n| misc                = \n}}\n\nThe '''''Quattro pezzi sacri''''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8kwattro \u02c8p\u025bttsi \u02c8sa\u02d0kri}}, ''Four Sacred Pieces'') are choral works by [[Giuseppe Verdi]]. Written separately during the last decades of the composer's life and with different origins and purposes, they were nevertheless published together in 1898 by [[Casa Ricordi]]. They are often performed as a cycle, not in chronological sequence of their composition, but in the sequence used in the Ricordi publication:\n* '''Ave Maria''', a setting of the [[Latin]] [[Ave Maria]] for four solo voices [[a cappella]] composed in 1889  \n* '''Stabat Mater''', a setting of the Latin [[Stabat Mater]] for chorus and orchestra composed in 1896 and 1897 \n* '''Laudi alla Vergine Maria''', a setting of a prayer in Canto XXXIII of [[Dante]]'s ''[[Paradiso (Dante)|Paradiso]]'' for four female voices a cappella composed between 1886 and 1888 \n* '''Te Deum''', a setting of the Latin [[Te Deum]] for double chorus and orchestra composed in 1895 and 1896.\n\nThey were first performed together (without the Ave Maria) in a concert by the [[Paris Opera]] on April 7, 1898.\n\n== History ==\n\nAfter Verdi finished his opera ''[[Aida]]'' and in 1874 the [[Requiem (Verdi)|Messa da Requiem]], he retired from composing for years, writing only minor sacred compositions such as a Pater Noster and an Ave Maria in 1880.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=351}} The earliest of the ''Quattro pezzi sacri'' in terms of its composition date is what came to be known as Laudi alla Vergine Maria (although Verdi himself did not give it that title).{{sfn|Izzo|2013|p= 318}} It was composed between 1886 and 1888, during which time he was also working on his penultimate opera, ''[[Otello]]'', which premiered in 1887. The second of the ''Pezzi'' to be composed was the Ave Maria, whose setting is built on an [[enigmatic scale]]. He originally composed it in 1889 and revised it for publication in 1897. The Te Deum was begun in 1895 two years after the premiere of his last opera, ''[[Falstaff (opera)|Falstaff]]''. It was finished in the summer of 1896. The Stabat Mater followed, and all four pieces were sent to Verdi's publisher, [[Casa Ricordi]], in June 1897.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=145}}\n\n== Music ==\nAt the end of his life Verdi returned to his beginnings as a church musician.{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}}  He studied [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]'s [[Mass in B minor structure|Mass in B minor]] and compositions by [[Giovanni Pierluigi da Palestrina|Palestrina]],{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} whose influence is apparent in the Laudi alla Vergine Maria.\n\nThe publisher [[Schott Music|Schott]] gives the total performance time as 37 minutes.<ref name=\"Schott\">''[https://archive.is/20131009105052/http://www.schott-music.com/shop/noten/eulenburg_studien-partituren/1660493/1261864/show,47227.html Four Sacred Pieces]'' [[Schott Music|Schott]]. Retrieved 9 October 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Ave Maria ===\n[[File:Scala enigmatica.svg|Enigmatic scale on C, base for Verdi's Ave Maria]]\n\nVerdi was inspired in 1889 to compose Ave Maria by the [[enigmatic scale]] C \u2013 D-flat \u2013 E \u2013 F-sharp \u2013 G-sharp \u2013 A-sharp \u2013 B \u2013 C which [[Adolfo Crescentini]] (1854\u20131921) had published in Ricordi's magazine ''Gazetta musicale di Milano'', inviting composers to harmonise it.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=135}} Verdi composed a setting for four unaccompanied voices, with the [[Bass (voice type)|bass]] singing the scale first, followed by [[alto]], [[tenor]] and [[soprano]], whereas the three remaining voices supply harmonic texture.{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} He commented: \"An Ave Maria. It will be my fourth! Perhaps I shall be beatified by the Holy Father.\"{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=135}} Verdi revised the work in June 1897 for the publication.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=145}} The music publisher [[Schott Music|Schott]] renders the subtitle as \"Scala enigmatica armonizzata a 4 voci miste\" (Enigmatic scale harmonised for four mixed voices).<ref name=\"Schott\" /> It takes about six minutes to perform.\n\n=== Stabat Mater ===\nWhile Ave Maria is set for soloists, Verdi scored the Stabat Mater for a four-part mixed chorus ([[SATB]]) and a large orchestra of three [[flute]]s, two [[oboe]]s, two [[clarinet]]s. four [[bassoon]]s, four [[French horn|horn]]s, three [[trumpet]]s, four [[trombone]]s, [[percussion]] ([[timpani]] and [[bass drum]]), [[harp]] and [[string instrument|string]]s.\n\nThe work is through-composed, without repetition of text. It is full of chromaticism. Melodic parts, similar to arias, contrast with [[a cappella]] passages and dramatic outbursts. The music reaches a climax on the text \"Paradisi gloria\" (glory of paradise), then dies down in the lowest registers of the strings.{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} A performance takes about 12 minutes.\n\n=== Laudi alla Vergine Maria ===\nLaudi alla Vergine Maria is another a cappella work, set for four solo female voices. It is based on a short prayer from in Canto XXXIII of Dantes's ''[[Paradiso (Dante)|Paradiso]]'', the third part of his ''[[Divina Commedia]]''. Verdi alludes on the counterpoint of [[Renaissance music]]. Each stanza is introduced by a new motif. Biographer Budden describes the piece as \"with the subtlest of harmonic and rhythmic inflexions, unashamedly modern in character\". The audience requested a repetition when it was first performed.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|pp=352\u2013353}}{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} Publisher Schott renders the subtitle as \"Tolte dall' ultimo canto del \"Paradiso\" di Dante per 4 voci feminili, sole\" (Taken from the ultimate song of \"Paradiso\" by Dante for 4 female voices, solo).<ref name=\"Schott\" /> It takes about six minutes to perform.\n\n=== Te Deum ===\nThe Ambrosian Hymn Te Deum is scored for two four-part choirs, a short soprano solo and large orchestra, adding [[cor anglais]] and [[bass clarinet]] to the orchestra of the ''Stabat Mater'', but without harp.{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} Verdi wrote to Giovanni Tebaldini, director of music in Padua: \"It is usually sung during grand, solemn and noisy ceremonies for a victory or a coronation etc. ... Humanity believes in the Judex Venturus, invokes Him in the Salvum fac and ends with a prayer, 'Dignare Domine die isto', which is moving, melancholy and sad even to the point of terror.\"{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=145}} The music begins with the [[Gregorian chant]] ''Te deum laudamus, te Dominum confitemur'', continued [[Responsory|responsorially]] by the whole male choir in [[unison]]. The full choir and orchestra enter in partly dramatic scenes, reminiscent of the Messa da Requiem,{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} interspersed by Gregorian chant. The final line ''in te speravi'' is first rendered by a single soprano voice from the choir, representing the \"[voice of] mankind\", as Verdi requested. The line is repeated by the choir, followed by a reticent postlude, similar to the conclusion of the [[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]].{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}} A performance takes about 15 minutes. Verdi himself suggested 12 minutes.\n\n== Performances ==\nVerdi did not want the Ave Maria to be performed with the other pieces.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=353}} According to his wish, three pieces were first performed on 7 and 8 April 1898 at the [[Paris Opera]] as part of a concert series of the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Concerts du Conservatoire, conducted by [[Paul Taffanel]] (1844\u20131908). Verdi was not present, because he had suffered a mild stroke, but sent [[Arrigo Boito]] with several requests, partly in writing, for performance details. The first performance in Italy, again without the ''Ave Maria'', was conducted in [[Turin]] on 26 May 1898 by [[Arturo Toscanini]] who had talked to Verdi. The first performance in Austria on 13 November 1898 in Vienna was conducted by [[Richard von Perger]] and included the ''Ave Maria'',{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=353}} but the two a cappella works were performed by the choir, not by solo voices as Verdi had intended.{{sfn|Schweikert|2001|pp=504\u2013507}}\n\nVerdi liked the Te Deum best of the four works and reputedly wanted to be buried with the score.{{sfnp|Budden|2008|p=358}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{cite book|ref=harv | last = Budden | first = Julian | url = https://books.google.com/?id=wKpapMfOp8kC&dq=Quattro+pezzi+sacri,+verdi | title = Verdi | year = 2008 | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | accessdate = 8 October 2013|isbn=9780198043485}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv |editor-first= Anselm |editor-last = Gerhard | editor-first2=Uwe | editor-last2=Schweikert |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=vXo3AQAAIAAJ|first=Uwe|last=Schweikert | chapter= Quattro pezzi sacri |title=Verdi Handbuch| year = 2001 | publisher = Metzler | location = Metzler Kassel, B\u00e4renreiter Stuttgart and Weimar |isbn=9783476017680|language=German }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv |last=Izzo|first= Francesco|editor-last=Di Grazia|editor-first=Donna M. |chapter=A Tale of Survival: Choral Music in Italy|title=Nineteenth-Century Choral Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AMog9DiN0jAC&pg=PA318|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415988520|page=318}}\n{{refend}}\n* Rizzo, Dino (2014). \"La Musica filosofica nei tre Pezzi sacri di Verdi\". In ''Atti del Convegno Verdi, la Musica e il Sacro, Roncole Verdi - Busseto, 27-29 settembre 2013'' a cura di Dino Rizzo, Fidenza, Mattioli 1885. {{ISBN|9788862614382}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMSLP|work=4 Pezzi sacri (Verdi, Giuseppe)|cname=Quattro pezzi sacri}}\n* {{ChoralWiki|Ave_Maria_(Giuseppe_Verdi)|Giuseppe Verdi: Ave Maria}}\n* {{ChoralWiki|Laudi_alla_Vergine_Maria_(Giuseppe_Verdi)|Giuseppe Verdi: Laudi alla Vergine Maria}}\n* {{DNB portal|30016615X}}\n* [http://www.allmusic.com/composition/sacred-pieces-4-for-chorus-orchestra-quattro-pezzi-sacri-mc0002363490 Giuseppe Verdi / Sacred Pieces (4), for chorus & orchestra (Quattro pezzi sacri)] [[Allmusic]]\n* Irina Georgieva: [https://urresearch.rochester.edu/fileDownloadForInstitutionalItem.action?itemId=26100&itemFileId=86306 Giuseppe Verdi's Quattro Pezzi Sacri: Early History and Programming Considerations, Analysis, and Interpretation] [[Eastman School of Music]], Rochester, New York\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150610202753/http://www.carus-verlag.com/index.php3?selSprache=1&BLink=KKArtikel&ArtNummer=2750000 Verdi\u2019s Quattro Pezzi Sacri] [[Carus-Verlag]]\n\n{{Giuseppe Verdi|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Giuseppe Verdi]]\n[[Category:Choral compositions]]\n[[Category:Stabat Mater settings]]\n[[Category:Te Deums|Verdi]]\n[[Category:1898 compositions]]\n[[Category:Musical settings of poems by Dante Alighieri]]\n", "name_user": "Jcspurrell", "label"